I would like the ``ThreadException`` event that is in the ``System.Windows.Forms`` assembly at https://github.com/dotnet/winforms/ to be in ``System.Environment`` in the ``System.Runtime`` or ``System.Runtime.Extensions`` assemblies because of the fact that a console application that spauns new threads that can possible throw exceptions that are possible not handled are not handled forcing the user to reference winforms just for plugging into that event. Maybe having the event moved to the ``System.Environment`` class and have the ``Application`` class's version of the event be a stub for this one for backwards compat and not cut from the ``ThreadExceptionDialog`` there too. Just being forced to reference the Windows Forms dependency just for a event that might be executing from a faulting thread spawned from ``System.Threading.Tasks`` is a pain in the butt. I am filing this issue as it has a long time been a painful issue of mine. I would like this changed for others to be able to use too. Also thread exception handling is already a xplat part of windows forms anyway am I right? I think moving it and stubbing it where it is now should not break anything (or well should not).

I would take a crack at the moving here on this issue as well, I just do not know all the parts of the code in the winforms repo that it would take to relocate to the ``Environment`` class. I would like some help.

And not to mention having the ``ThreadException`` event only be in winforms seems like a flaw in the implementation of the framework because it could be deployed from any thread.

