This difference occurs due to openssl doesn't verify certificate in the second time ([`internal_verify`](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/902f3f50d051dfd6ebf009d352aaf581195caabf/crypto/x509/x509_vfy.c#L1754-L1777)):
```cpp
        if (!xs->valid
            && (xs != xi
                || (ctx->param->flags & X509_V_FLAG_CHECK_SS_SIGNATURE))) {
            if ((pkey = X509_get_pubkey(xi)) == NULL) {
                ctx->error = X509_V_ERR_UNABLE_TO_DECODE_ISSUER_PUBLIC_KEY;
                ctx->current_cert = xi;
                ok = (*cb) (0, ctx);
                if (!ok)
                    goto end;
            } else if (X509_verify(xs, pkey) <= 0) {
                ctx->error = X509_V_ERR_CERT_SIGNATURE_FAILURE;
                ctx->current_cert = xs;
                ok = (*cb) (0, ctx);
                if (!ok) {
                    EVP_PKEY_free(pkey);
                    goto end;
                }
            }
            EVP_PKEY_free(pkey);
            pkey = NULL;
        }

        xs->valid = 1;
```

As corefx's [callback](https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/b30e7723c98a6e7da0fa7d6edd4a54643275afad/src/System.Security.Cryptography.X509Certificates/src/Internal/Cryptography/Pal.Unix/OpenSslX509ChainProcessor.cs#L896) returns 1 in the case of error we don't go to `end` label and set `xs->valid` to 1.

Is it expected behavior?

